Membership[edit]
TDBFG is a member of the Canadian Bankers Association (CBA) and registered member with the Canada Deposit Insurance Corporation (CDIC), a Government of Canada agency insuring deposits at all of Canada's chartered banks. It is also a member of:

Interac
NYCE ATM network
Plus Network for VISA cards
VISA International
Canadian Investor Protection Fund

Sponsorships[edit]
The Toronto-Dominion Bank and its subsidiaries own the naming rights to the following venues:

TD Ameritrade Park Omaha in Omaha, Nebraska, United States
TD Arena in Charleston, South Carolina, United States
TD Bank Arts Centre in Gloucester County, New Jersey, United States
TD Bank Ballpark in Bridgewater, New Jersey, United States
TD Bank Sports Center in Hamden, Connecticut, United States
TD Garden in Boston, Massachusetts, United States
TD Place Arena in Ottawa, Ontario, Canada
TD Place Stadium in Ottawa, Ontario, Canada
TD Stadium in London, Ontario, Canada

Credit agency ratings[edit]
After Moody's Investor Service downgraded the credit worthiness of Royal Bank of Canada to Aa1 on December 13, 2010, TD was the only of Canada's Big Five banks with a top Aaa credit rating (at the time CIBC was Aa2, Scotiabank Aa1 and Bank of Montreal was Aa2).[31] It is also ranked number 1 in the Top 1000 2012 listing.[32]
Controversies[edit]
News outlets reported the bank's policy regarding ordinary Iranian-Canadian citizens, July 10, 2012.[33] Some one hundred personal bank accounts had been closed to this date, citing the recent ambiguous Special Economic Measure Regulation of the Canadian government. A family in Vancouver was forced to refinance a $250,000 house mortgage in 60 days to avoid foreclosure.[33]
A TD Bank document became the focus of a recent contempt hearing in Miami federal court. In a civil lawsuit against TD Bank a jury found the bank liable for aiding Ponzi schemer Scott Rothstein's $1.4 billion fraud.[34]
In 2015, Canadian news website the Halifax Examiner reported that a Political action committee (PAC) established by TD Bank had donated over $50,000 to the campaigns of anti-LGBT rights politicians in the United States.[35] The article suggested that this was problematic given TD Bank's status as a sponsor of 41 LGBT Pride events across North America; TD Bank made no comment. In response to this article, on October 6, 2015 a motion was brought at the Annual General Meeting of Halifax Pride to sever ties with TD Bank if it did not provide a satisfactory response to the concerns; the motion was ultimately defeated.[36]
On March 10, 2017, the Canadian Broadcasting Corporation's (CBC) news programme Go Public reported that TD Bank employees had admitted that, under pressure to achieve sale's targets, they had increased customers' lines of credit, overdraft amounts, and Visa credit limits without advising them which is against the law. One TD financial adviser says she "invested clients' savings into funds which were not suitable, because of the SR [sales revenue] pressure". Another admitted downplaying the risk of products saying: "I was forced to lie to customers, just to meet the sales revenue targets." In an internal letter to employees, Andy Pilkington, executive vice-president of branch banking, wrote: "We don't believe the [CBC] story is an accurate portrayal of our culture," but the report provided an opportunity "to pause, reflect and ask ourselves ... how we can do better for our people and our customers."[37] The bank's stock lost 5.55% of its value on March 10th declining by $3.88 (Cdn) per share to close at $66.00 (Cdn).[38]
Branch locations[edit]
As of January 2014 TD operates the sixth largest branch network in North America with 1,100 TD Canada Trust offices and 1,300 TD Bank (U.S.) offices. While its network extends across Canada and the U.S. Atlantic coast, customers of either the Canadian and U.S. component are not able to perform a full range of transactions at a branch of the other component. It does allow an expanded range of transactions to customers who register their accounts for its Cross-Border Banking program.[39]
TD operates 2,800 ATMs in Canada and 1,900 in the U.S. for a total of 4,700,[40] and allows customers of either component to withdraw funds in the U.S. or Canada without Plus Network or Presto! transaction surcharges.


